So Chidi sends me this breathless text: “Marisol, you’re not spending your down payment? You’re just *leaving* it in a savings account? You know that’s losing value, right?” I’m like, “Uh, yeah, that’s kind of the point—it’s safe.” He says, “Safe? That’s called *leaving money on the table*. My cousin’s killing it on options. One call, three weeks ago—he turned eight grand into thirty-two. Thirty-two!”

I didn’t want to sound like a dummy, so I start looking. And within two days, I’ve downloaded an app, read a blog post about gamma squeezes, and I’m laddering short puts on a small biotech stock that just had phase two results.

—Hana, come on.

I know. I know. But you don’t understand—Chidi kept saying things like, “Opportunity cost is the real tax.” Like it was *profound*. Like he’d cracked the code.

Then Marisol—my sister, not your friend at work—calls me Tuesday night. “You liquidated the down payment fund?” I say, “Just a piece of it.” She says, “You *what*?” I explain the strategy. She says, “You gave your house money to a *strangle play* and you think you’re being *smart*?”

I go quiet. She says, “Chidi’s idea?”

I said yeah.

She laughs. Not teasing. Angry-laugh. “So the guy who lost six grand on a cryptocurrency because a *podcast* said it was ‘undervalued’—that’s your financial advisor now?”

I didn’t say that.

You *are* saying it. Every time you repeat his nonsense.

—Anyway. The position’s underwater. Not wiped out. But not breathing right either.

So what now?

I froze the account. Transferred back what I could. Waited. Watched it swing. Thought about calling Chidi.

Did you?

I haven’t. Phone’s right here. Screen’s cracked. I keep picking it up, then putting it down.

