Ingrid had been saving for two years—$38,000 salted away for a down payment, stashed in a conservative money-market fund that barely beat inflation but never made her heart race. Then Dmitri started texting. "This options strategy," he said, "it’s not gambling. It’s math. Volatility is just mispriced opportunity." He’d made 14% in three weeks, he told her, on a small biotech stock. "You hold through the noise," he said, like it was wisdom. "These aren’t lottery tickets. Look at the Greeks. I’ve backtested this."

She wavered. Homeownership felt abstract—something for later, when life slowed down. But Dmitri’s confidence was magnetic. He wasn’t some boiler-room broker; he was her brother’s best friend who fixed his own car and talked about compound interest like scripture. He sent screenshots, spreadsheets. He said things like, "Liquidity is your friend" and "Risk management means knowing your exit." When Ingrid mentioned her deposit goal, Chidi overheard, raised an eyebrow. "So you trust him more than your future?"

She paused. For a week. Then the stock dipped. Dmitri called: "Perfect entry window. You’re not scared, are you?" That did it. She moved $22,000 into a leverage-heavy position. The stock collapsed two days later on trial results. Her broker emailed: "Market risk cannot be eliminated."

Now, the apartment she wanted is under contract. Ingrid checks her options dashboard every morning, same time. Dmitri stopped replying.

"Options aren’t reckless," he’d said once, grinning. "Only if you use them like they’re cash."

