------------------------------------------------------------------------------
—Posted by Ingrid at 03:18

Marisol showed up at my door with a printout. Said she’d “cracked it.” Portfolio theory sketched in highlighter. Had run the numbers, she claimed. Her cousin Kofi’s strategy—leveraged call options on a small biotech stock—was “the only math that makes sense now.” I’d just pulled $47K from a CD, house deposit, sitting in my emergency fund. Marisol didn’t blink. “Park it in three-month calls, 8x leverage. You’ll triple it before closing. Guaranteed.”

She talked like she’d discovered gravity. Not possibility. Certainty. Said the book said so. Not one book—“the good ones,” she said. “All the authors agree now: risk is just a timing problem.” I asked about the volatility. She laughed. “Only if you panic and sell. Kofi held through a 30% drop. Got out at 2.8x. Textbook.”

I believed her. Not because I’m naive—but because she’d used words I trusted: allocation, delta, time decay. Spoke like she’d studied, like she’d won something. That’s what makes these people dangerous—they don’t sound like gamblers. They sound like relief.

Turns out Kofi didn’t triple anything. He lost 70%, then doubled down. Marisol left that part out. My rent’s due in eleven days.

There’s a book you all keep recommending—calm, graphs on risk tolerance, the one with the mountain on the cover. I flipped through it in the airport. Page 62: “Risk is survivable if the downside doesn’t alter your life trajectory.” That’s the test. That’s the line.

But no one who hands you a trading strategy ever asks what happens if you lose. They assume you’re playing. They assume you have a second pot.

Delete Marisol’s number, if you have one. Don’t ask what she meant. Ask why she didn’t care what she meant.

I’m calling the credit union tomorrow. Ask if they offer loan extensions for people who listened to people like her.

