 topic: margin trading as a beginner investor
 focus: practical guidance on what to do instead
 register: plainspoken | audience: young professionals | quirk: begin in the middle of a specific situation, no preamble
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Felix showed up Wednesday with his laptop open like it meant something, grinning like he’d cracked the code. “Dmitri’s up twenty percent in two weeks,” he said, “just riding a biotech runner with margin.” Like that explained everything. Like saying the word *margin* didn’t sound like a warning label. He didn’t say “if it goes wrong,” didn’t mention the call, didn’t ask if I had an emergency fund, a pension plan, rent due. Just: *You could do this too.*  

Noor, same day, tagged me in a post—some long thread about a cryptocurrency pumping overnight, one of those coins that lives or dies on three tweets. “Could 10x?” she wrote. “You can borrow against your holdings, right?” I almost laughed. Not because it’s dumb—because she *works in compliance*. She knows better. But the idea of leverage, of *getting more with less*, made her pupils dilate. Same look Dmitri had when he bought in.  

It’s not that they want you to lose. That’s not the point. The point is, they don’t care. They’re *excited*. And that’s worse. Excitement is the engine of bad decisions. They’re not predators in a boardroom; they’re the guy next to you on the train who just got rich and now everything he touches is gospel. He’ll hand you dynamite like it’s a pen.  

Look: margin as a beginner isn’t investing. It’s borrowing money to bet on a feeling. If you’re new—if you can’t yet recognize your own panic when a stock dips 5%—margin turns that panic into a eviction notice. You don’t learn the market that way. You learn how fast brokers liquidate your account when you can’t cover the call.  

Instead? Open the boring account. The one that lets you buy $50 of an index fund every paycheck. Set it on autopilot. Don’t look at it more than once a month. That’s the hard part, right? Staying away. But that’s also how you win.  

I told Felix I’d sleep on it. I didn’t. I transferred $200 into the fund I set up last year, the one he thinks is for “retirement someday.” It’s not. It’s for not being broke next month.  

Noor never responded to my question about what happens if that coin drops 70% overnight.  

I’ll add another $100 next Friday. Same time. Same fund.

