**Q: How do I know if the financial advice I’m getting is actually safe—especially if it sounds promising?**  
**A:** Be suspicious of anyone who frames high risk as opportunity, especially when your time for recovery is short. Promising is not the same as sound. It’s the delivery—confident, casual, cloaked in “everyone’s doing it”—that blindsides people.  

Take Elena, for instance. Former HR administrator. Conservative portfolio for two decades—bonds, index funds, dividend payers. Then, last spring, her coworker Yuki starts pulling her aside after meetings. Not pushy, just “sharing.” Said her cousin had pulled out of “low-growth relics” and doubled his money in eight months on a biotech play—some small company with one drug trial pending. “It’s not speculative,” Yuki kept saying, “it’s strategic.” Elena mentioned she was down to five years from retiring. Yuki’s response? “That’s exactly why you need this now. Time is your enemy if you stay in bonds.”  

Same week, neighbor Ingrid corners her at the mailbox. Got wind from Yuki of the conversation—funny how these things spread—and chirps about “digital assets.” Said her son moved a chunk of emergency savings into a cryptocurrency because “banks are dead.” She didn’t mention the one-time loss that had wiped out half of that same account two months earlier. Just smiled and said, “You’re too careful, Elena. The real risk is falling behind.”  

Elena started to listen. She pulled her quarterly statement—saw the steady, modest numbers, felt the familiar pinch of worry. Then she started moving money. Quiet shifts at first—$12,000 into the biotech stock, 8% into the digital asset fund. Her financial advisor had warned her. Said the volatility was not aligned with her timeline or tolerance. She stopped returning his calls.  

Then the biotech failed its Phase III results. Stock dropped 76% in two days. Cryptocurrency got tangled in regulatory scrutiny. Another 40% gone. Not her entire portfolio—but the part she’d shifted, the part she’d thought was “catching up.”  

She froze. Cold. Sat at her table for three hours staring at the screen. Then picked up the phone. Called the advisor back. Not to apologize. To say, “Make it safe. All of it. Today.”  

Turns out, Yuki’s cousin bailed out a week before the crash—“lucky timing,” he called it. Ingrid’s son withdrew everything when the exchange went dark for 48 hours—“a scare, but we’re fine.”  

This isn’t about bad luck. It’s about people who feel clever for skating over fire, then turn around and hand you a torch. They don’t see the risk. Or worse—they see it and call it a shortcut.  

I remember my cousin—same story, different year. Told me a “private pre-IPO play” would 3x in 18 months. “Guaranteed.” I didn’t take it, but I kept turning it over in my mind. That itch to believe. That’s what they count on.  

Elena’s recovery took nine months. Rebalanced, re-secured, reinvested in instruments that don’t promise, just perform. But she still gets emails—Ingrid, bless her, sent a “new opportunity” last week: a startup in sustainable fuel. “Thought of you!”  

I’ll ask Elena if she replied. Hers is the only judgment I trust now.

