Owen. Mid-thirties. Thought he was being smart. Tech bubble blowing up in the rearview, crypto round two starting to tick. His cousin Devon—someone who’s never owned a savings account—sits him down at a barbecue, mouth full of chicken, says: “You’re leaving money on the table. Retirement’s thirty years away. This isn’t gambling, it’s *timing*.”

Saw a 40 percent run on a small biotech stock. Peers were cashing out 401(k)s, taking on loans, just to get in. His coworker Sanjay had a second screen just for tracking gains. “You don’t wait for permission,” he said. “You *act*.”

So Owen did. Pulled half his balance. Tax hit, yeah. Penalty, sure. But everyone else was winning. For two weeks.

Then the pullback hit. Hard. Biotech stock cratered. Cryptocurrency got vaporized in a cascade. Sanjay stopped coming in on Fridays. Devon stopped returning texts.

Owen’s still paying off the loan. Still has to explain to his kid why the college fund is empty.

And the worst part? Nobody feels bad. They just pivot. Now it’s real estate. Now it’s a “private opportunity.” Same tone. Same grin.

I saw Owen last week. He handed his kid a library card. Said it was the only investment he trusts now.
